label.name: Title Types
label.description: This field should NOT be filled out! Enter Title Type in the drop down in the Title field above.

label.name: Description
label.description: The metadata element description uses free-form text or a narrative to report general notes, abstracts, or summaries about the intellectual content of a media item you are cataloging. The information may be in the form of a paragraph giving an individual program description, anecdotal interpretations, or brief content reviews. The description may also consist of outlines, lists, bullet points, rundowns, segment sequence, edit decision lists, indexes, or tables of content.

label.name: Temporal coverage
label.description: Enter a date/time or range of date/times. You can be a specific (eg. 07/14/2001 @ 10:54:01am) or as general (circa 2001) as required.

label.name: Spatial coverage
label.description: Enter an address or locality name. Your input will be converted automatically to map coordinates.

label.name: Identifier (pbcore)
label.description: Each NHF IC record should only have 1 identifier. This Identifier (pbcore) field was created only for the migration of ProCite records. New IC records should not have any data in the Identifier (pbcore) field, only the Identifier field, and all records containing data there must be cleaned up (data moved into the correct identifier field and the Identifier (pbcore) field delete.

label.name: Subject
label.description: The descriptor subject is used to assign topical headings or keywords that portray the intellectual content of the media item you are cataloging. Typically, a subject is expressed by a limited number of keywords, key phrases, or even specific classification codes.

label.name: Genre
label.description: The descriptor genre describes the manner in which the intellectual content of a media item is presented, viewed or heard by a user. It indicates the structure of the presentation, as well as the topical nature of the content in a generalized form.

label.name: Relation
label.description: The descriptor relationType identifies the type of intellectual content bond between a media item you are cataloging and some other related media item. Once the type of relationship between two media items is identified by using the descriptor relationType, then this companion descriptor relationIdentifier is used to provide a name, locator, accession, identification number or ID where the related item can be obtained or found. The cross reference uses a unique identifier.

label.name: Audience Level
label.description: The descriptor audienceLevel identifies a type of audience, viewer, or listener for whom the media item you are cataloging is primarily designed or educationally useful.

label.name: Audience Rating
label.description: The descriptor audienceRating designates the type of users for whom a media item is intended or judged appropriate in terms of its intellectual content. Standard ratings have been crafted by the broadcast television and film industries and are used as flags for audience or age-appropriate materials.

label.name: Rights Summary
label.description: Information about rights held in and over the resource.

label.name: Date Created
label.description: Use the descriptor dateCreated to specify the creation date for a particular version or rendition of a media item across its life cycle. It is the moment in time that the media item was finalized during its production process and is forwarded to other divisions or agencies to make it ready for publication or distribution.

label.name: Date Issued
label.description: The descriptor dateIssued specifies the formal date for a particular version or rendition of a media item has been made ready or officially released for distribution, publication or consumption.

Format: Standard
label.description: Use the descriptor formatStandard to identify a larger technical system/standard or overarching media architecture under which various media formats exist, e.g., NTSC is a system/standard under which many video formats exist.

label.name: Format: Encoding
label.description: The descriptor formatEncoding identifies how the actual information in a media item is compressed, interpreted, or formulated using a particular scheme. Identifying the encoding used is beneficial for a number of reasons, including as a way to achieve reversible compression; for the construction of document indices to facilitate searching and access; or for efficient distribution of the information across data networks with differing bandwidths or pipeline capacities.

label.name: Format: Sampling Rate
label.description: For a media item (specifically audio), the descriptor formatSamplingRate measures "How Often " data is sampled when information is digitized. For a digital audio signal, the sampling rate is measured in kiloHertz and is an indicator of the perceived playback quality of the media item (the higher the sampling rate, the greater the fidelity).

label.name: Format: Frame Size
label.description: he descriptor formatFrameSize indicates the horizontal and vertical resolution of a format type. It may be expressed in pixels, pixels per inch, or in the case of ATSC digital TV, a combination of pixels measured horizontally vs. the number of pixels of image/resolution data stacked vertically (interlaced and progressive scan).

label.name: Format: Aspect Ratio
label.description: The descriptor formatAspectRatio indicates the ratio of horizontal to vertical proportions in the display of an static image or moving image.

label.name: Format: Frame Rate
label.description: The descriptor formatFrameRate indicates the frames per second found in a video, motion sequence, flash file, or animation's playback or display.

label.name: Collection summary
label.description:
"DACS 3.1 Scope and Content: First sentence: A statement listing the physical contents of the collection (including reels of film, published books, film equipment – whatever is accessioned into the collection), including creator and creation dates. Next 3-4 sentences: Statements highlighting the main topics, events, locations, people, etc. within the collection. Last sentence: End the paragraph with a statement highlighting the most important or significant items in the collection. If there aren’t any specific dates, places or people, then make a general statement about what makes the collection significant – a final statement aimed at potential researchers.
This element provides information about the nature of the materials and activities reflected in the unit being described to enable users to judge its potential relevance. See additional rules in Chapter 3.1 for details."

label.name: Biographical and historical notes
label.description: "DACS 10.0 Administrative/Biographical History: The purpose of this element is to provide information about the organization(s) or individual(s) associated in some way with the creation, assembly, accumulation, and/or maintenance and use of the unit being described in order to place the material in context and make it better understood. See additional rules in Chapter 10 for details."

label.name: Collection date span
label.description: "DACS 2.4.7 Date Ranges: If the materials comprising or the record-keeping activity relating to the unit being described span a period of time, always record the inclusive dates, that is, the earliest and latest dates of the materials or activity in question. See section 2.4 for additional rules on Dates."

label.name: System of Arrangement
label.description: "DACS 3.2 System of Arrangement: The element identifies the various aggregations of archival materials, their relationships, or the sequence of documents within them. See section 3.2 for additional rules."

label.name: Language Materials
label.description:
A statement expressing the language(s) of the archival materials found in the collection being described. Language of the material may also be recorded in coded form in the LANGCODE attribute in the <language> subelement using the ISO 639-2b three-letter language codes.
Do not confuse with the Language Usage <langusage> element which specifies the language(s) in which the finding aid is written. See also the description for the <language> element.

label.name: Language Materials Statement
label.description: Enter a brief statement of the languages used in the materials being described, or a statement indicating an absence of language materials in exclusively visual collections. Examples: "No textual or other language materials are included in the collection" "Intertitles and can notes are in English." "Collection includes sound materials in English language."

label.name: Language Materials Code
